\begin_layout Abstract
The fluctuation-response relation, a central result in non-equilibrium statistic
al mechanics, relates equilibrium fluctuations in a system to its linear
 response to external forces.
 Here we provide a direct experimental verification of this relation for
 viscously coupled oscillators, as realized by a pair of optically trapped
 colloidal particles.
 A theoretical analysis, in which interactions mediated by slow viscous
 flow are represented by non-local friction tensors, matches experimental
 results and reveals a frequency maximum in the amplitude of the mutual
 response which is a sensitive function of the trap stiffnesses and the
 friction tensors.
 This allows for its location and width to be tuned independently and suggests
 the utility of the trap setup for accurate two-point microrheology.
\end_layout

